{{refimprove|date=June 2016}}
[[File:HawawishRockTombs.jpg|thumb|right|250px|Rock tombs at El Hawawish]]
'''El Hawawish''' ({{lang-ar|الحواويش}}) is the name given to the site of the ancient [[necropolis]] (cemetery) for the city of [[Akhmim]] in the [[Sohag Governorate]], [[Egypt]].

The cemetery was excavated extensively by an [[Australia]]n archaeological and epigraphic expedition under the auspices of the [[Australian Centre for Egyptology]] and [[Macquarie University]] and the direction of Professor [[Naguib Kanawati]].

{{Commons category|El-Hawawish}}

{{coord|26|36|N|31|49|E|region:EG_type:city_source:enwiki-GNS|display=title}}

== History ==

=== Ancient ===
Similar to nearby Akhmim, the local deity of El Hawawish was the fertility and productivity god Min.

Tombs of the [[Old Kingdom of Egypt|Old Kingdom]] and [[First Intermediate Period of Egypt|First Intermediate Period]] are located in the El Hawawish mountain.<ref>{{Cite book|title=Sohag in Upper Egypt: A Glorious History|last=Kanawati|first=Naguib|last2=Scannell|first2=Reece|publisher=Prism Archaeological Series 4|year=1990|isbn=9772350025|location=Giza|pages=16}}</ref>

== Bibliography ==
