'''Avaris''' ({{IPAc-en|ˈ|æ|v|ə|r|ᵻ|s}}; [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]]: ḥw.t wꜥr.t, sometimes transcribed ''Hut-waret'' in works for a popular audience, {{lang-el|Αὔαρις}}, {{lang|el-Latn|Auaris}})<ref>Holladay, John S. Jr. (1997) "The Eastern Nile Delta During the Hyksos and Pre-Hyksos Periods: Toward a Systemic/Socioeconomic Understanding", in {{cite book|author=Eliezer D. Oren|title=The Hyksos: new historical and archaeological perspectives|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=oiKLQgAACAAJ|year=1997|publisher=University Museum, University of Pennsylvania|isbn=978-0-924171-46-8|pages=183–252}}</ref> was the capital of Egypt under the [[Hyksos]]. It was located at modern [[Tell el-Dab'a]] in the northeastern region of the [[Nile Delta]], at the juncture of the 8th, 14th, 19th and 20th [[Nome (Egypt)|Nomes]].<ref>Baines and Malek "Atlas of Ancient Egypt" p 15 nome list and map, p 167 enlarged map of the delta.</ref> As the main course of the Nile migrated eastward, its position at the hub of Egypt's delta emporia made it a major administrative capital of the [[Hyksos]] and other traders.<ref name="Grant2005">{{cite book|author=Michael Grant|title=The rise of the Greeks|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=vl-MgnNXpmQC|year=2005|publisher=[[Barnes & Noble Books]] |isbn=978-0-7607-7000-9}}</ref> It was occupied from about 1783 to 1550&nbsp;BC, or from the [[Thirteenth Dynasty of Egypt]] through the second intermediate period until its destruction by [[Ahmose I]], the first Pharaoh of the [[Eighteenth dynasty of Egypt|Eighteenth dynasty]]. The name in the [[Egyptian language]] of the 2nd millennium BC was probably pronounced '''*Ḥaʔat-Wūrat''' 'Great House' and denotes the capital of an administrative division of the land. Today, the name ''Hawara'' survives, referring to the site at the entrance to [[Faiyum]]. Alternatively, [[Clement of Alexandria]] referred to the name of this city as "Athyria".<ref>'And his remarks are to the following effect: Amosis, who lived in the time of the Argive Inachus, overthrew Athyria, as Ptolemy of Mendes [via Manetho] relates in his Chronology.' -- Clement of Alexandria 1.22</ref>

==Overview==
[[File:ScarabBearingNameOfApophis MuseumOfFineArtsBoston.png|thumb|150px|right|[[Scarab (artifact)|Scarab]] bearing the name of the Hyksos King [[Apepi (pharaoh)|Apepi]], now at the [[Museum of Fine Arts, Boston]]]]

In 1885, the [[Switzerland|Swiss]] [[Édouard Naville]] started the first excavations in the area around Tell-el-Daba. Between 1941 and 1942, [[Labib Habachi]], an [[Egypt]]ian [[Egyptologist]] first forwarded the idea that the site could be identified with Avaris. Between 1966 and 1969 and since 1975, the site has been excavated by the [[Austrian Archaeological Institute]].<ref name="Tell el-Dab'a - History">{{cite web|url=http://www.auaris.at/html/history_en.html|title=Tell el-Dab'a - History|publisher=Tell el-Dab'a-Homepage|accessdate=2010-06-21| archiveurl= https://web.archive.org/web/20100626102217/http://www.auaris.at/html/history_en.html| archivedate= 26 June 2010 <!--DASHBot-->| deadurl= no}}</ref> Using radar imaging technology, its scientists could identify in 2010 the outline of the city including streets, houses, a port, and a side arm of the River Nile passing through the city.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/world/middle_east/10367930.stm|title=Ancient Egyptian city located in Nile Delta by radar|publisher=BBC News|date=2010-06-21}}</ref>

The site at Tell el-Dab'a, covering an area of about 2 square kilometers, is in ruins today, but excavations have shown that, at one point, it was a well-developed center of trade with a busy harbour catering to over 300 ships during a trading season.<ref name="google">{{cite book|title=The Hyksos Period in Egypt|author=Booth, C.|date=2005|publisher=Shire|isbn=9780747806387|url=https://books.google.co.uk/books?id=srQmRwVozvkC&pg=PA40|page=40|accessdate=2016-02-03}}</ref>  Artifacts excavated at a temple erected in the Hyksos period have produced goods from all over the [[Aegean civilization|Aegean]] world. The temple even has [[Minoan civilization|Minoan]]-like wall paintings that are similar to those found on [[Crete]] at the [[Knossos|Palace of Knossos]]. A large [[mudbrick]] tomb has also been excavated to the west of the temple, where [[Grave goods|grave-goods]], such as copper swords, have been found.

Towards the end of the [[Seventeenth dynasty of Egypt|Seventeenth dynasty]], [[Kamose]], the last king of the [[Seventeenth dynasty of Egypt|Seventeenth Dynasty]], besieged Avaris, but could not dislodge the Hyksos, who were finally expelled some 18 years later (c. 1550&nbsp;BC) by [[Ahmose I]], the founder of the [[Eighteenth dynasty of Egypt|Eighteenth Dynasty]].<ref>Some claim that Kamose and Ahmose were the same person and that, after the capture of Avaris and the expulsion of the Hyksos made the founding of the [[Eighteenth dynasty of Egypt]] possible, Kamose changed his name (see discussion in Baines and Ma'lek)</ref> The Eighteenth Dynasty-based themselves in [[Thebes, Egypt|Thebes]] and Avaris was largely abandoned, its former citadel becoming the site first of enormous storage facilities, including numerous silos and then a military camp, until finally a new palatial compound of the 18th Dynasty was constructed on top of the camps and soldier graves.<ref name="Tell el-Dab'a - History"/> Avaris was absorbed into the new city of [[Pi-Ramesses]] constructed by [[Ramesses II]] (1279–1213&nbsp;BC) of the [[Nineteenth dynasty of Egypt|Nineteenth dynasty]] when he moved the capital back to the Delta.

==Minoan connection==
{{Further information|Minoan frescoes from Tell el-Daba}}
[[File:Minoan fresko avaris 2.png|thumb|300px|Fragment of a Minoan fresco found in Avaris, Egypt. This fresco is very similar to [[:Image:Knossos frise taureau.JPG|another fresco]] from [[Knossos]], [[Crete]].]]

Avaris, along with [[Tel Kabri]] in Israel and [[Alalakh]] in Syria, also has a record of [[Minoan civilization]], which is otherwise quite rare in the Levant. [[Manfred Bietak]], an Austrian archaeologist and the excavator of Tell Dab'a, has speculated that there was close contact with the rulers of Avaris, and that the large building representing the frescoes allowed the Minoans to have a ritual life in Egypt. French archaeologist Yves Duhoux proposed the existence of a Minoan 'colony' on an island in the Nile delta.<ref>{{cite book |last=Duhoux |first=Yves |title=Des minoens en Egypte? "Keftiou" et "les îles au milieu du Grand vert" |year=2003 |publisher=Univ. Press |location=Liège |isbn=90-429-1261-8 }}</ref>

