{{coord|23.2833|N|32.9000|E|source:wikidata|display=title}}
[[Category:Archaeological sites in Egypt]] [[Category:Egyptian temples]] [[Category:Relocated ancient Egyptian monuments]]

'''Zawyet Umm El Rakham''' ({{lang-arz|زاوية أم الرخم}} lit. "the resthouse of the mother of vultures")<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liverpool.ac.uk/archaeology-classics-and-egyptology/research/projects/zawiyet/|title=The Zawiyet Umm el-Rakham Project}}</ref> is located on the [[North coast of Egypt]] 20&nbsp;km to the west of [[Marsa Matruh]], and about 300&nbsp;km to the west of [[Alexandria]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022185436/http://geocities.com/zurdig/HomeFrame.htm|title=Zawiyet Umm el-Rakham}}</ref>
During the reign of [[Ramesses II]], it was the location of a major fortress-town which probably marked the western extent of direct [[Ancient Egypt|Egyptian]] influence.
It was discovered in 1948 and in the subsequent years was sporadically examined by [[Alan Rowe (archaeologist)|Alan Rowe]] and [[Labib Habachi]]. Since 1994 extensive excavations have been undertaken at the site by a team from the [[University of Liverpool]] under the direction of [[Steven Snape]].
==References== {{reflist}}
==Further reading== *S. Snape & P. Wilson ''Zawiyet Umm el-Rakham I: The Temple and Chapels'' (Rutherford Press, Bolton: 2007) *L. Habachi: ''The Military Posts of Ramesses II on the Coastal Road and the Western Part of the Delta'', in: ''BIFAO'' 80 (1980), S. 13-30 *S. R. Snape: ''Walls, Wells and Wandering Merchants: Egyptian Control of the Marmarica in the Late Bronze Age'' in: C.J. Eyre (Hrsg.), ''Proceedings of the Seventh International Congress of Egyptologists'', Leuven 1998, S. 1081-84 *S. R. Snape: ''The excavations of the Liverpool University Mission to Zawiyet Umm el-Rakham 1994-2001'', in: ''ASAE'' 78 (2004), S. 149-160, Kairo.
