'''El Qattah''', also known as '''Qattah''' or '''El-Qattah''', is an ancient Egyptian site in Lower Egypt, roughly 10 miles northwest of [[Letopolis]]. It is noted for its tombs of the [[Middle Kingdom of Egypt|Middle Kingdom]], and was excavated extensively in 1904 by a team from the [[Institut Français d'Archéologie Orientale]] of Cairo, a team which included [[Henri Gauthier]].<ref name="GriffithSociety1902">{{cite book|last=Griffith|first=Francis Llewellyn|title=Archaeological report|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=HRZXAAAAMAAJ|accessdate=21 October 2012|year=1902|publisher=Egypt Exploration Fund.|page=30}}</ref><ref name="DawsonUphill1972">{{cite book|last1=Dawson|first1=Warren Royal|last2=Uphill|first2=Eric Parrington|title=Who was who in Egyptology ...|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=xHVSVbY95S8C|accessdate=21 October 2012|date=December 1972|publisher=Egypt Exploration Society|page=114}}</ref> One of the chambers at the site contained texts from the [[Book of the Dead]].<ref name="GriffithSociety1902"/> The Tomb of [[Néha]] was discovered here.<ref name="Desplancques2006">{{cite book|last=Desplancques|first=Sophie|title=L'institution du trésor en Egypte des origines à la fin du Moyen Empire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Dpltn2UOrjAC&pg=RA1-PA132|accessdate=21 October 2012|year=2006|publisher=Presses Paris Sorbonne|isbn=978-2-84050-451-1|page=132}}</ref> In 1906 it was reported that a modern village is located here.<ref>{{cite book|title=Mémoires publiés par les membres de l'Institut français d'archéologie orientale du Caire|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=tfAwAQAAMAAJ|accessdate=21 October 2012|year=1906|publisher=Institut français d'archéologie orientale|pages=1–3}}</ref>

