'''Gynaecopolis''' (City of Women) is an ancient city in [[Lower Egypt]].
==History== It was known in Ancient Egypt as Per Nebet Imau.<ref name="cueflash1">{{Cite web|url=http://cueflash.com/decks/Shire_08_Nomes_Lower_Egypt|title=Shire 08 Nomes Lower Egypt-:- Flash cards by cueFlash|website=cueflash.com|language=en|access-date=2018-02-26}}</ref> It was the capital of the Gynaecopolite [[Nome (Egypt)|nome]] mentioned by [[Strabo]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://penelope.uchicago.edu/Thayer/E/Gazetteer/Places/Africa/Egypt/_Texts/BEVHOP/5B*.html |title=E. R. Bevan: The House of Ptolemy • Chap. V § 2 |publisher=Penelope.uchicago.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-10}}</ref> and coins having its impress in the age of [[Hadrian]] are still present.<ref name=PersGynaecopolis>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus%3Atext%3A1999.04.0064%3Aentry%3Dgynaecopolis-geo |title=Gynaecopolis| work=Dictionary of Greek and Roman Geography |publisher=Perseus.tufts.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-10}}</ref> It is sometimes thought to be the same town as [[Anthylla]].<ref name=PersAnthylla>{{cite web|url=http://www.perseus.tufts.edu/hopper/text?doc=Perseus:text:1999.04.0064:entry=anthylla-geo |title=Anthylla| work=Dictionary of Greek and Roman Geography |publisher=Perseus.tufts.edu |date= |accessdate=2012-11-10}}</ref> It may have been in the area of [[Kom el-Hisn]].<ref name="cueflash1"/>
==Origin of its name== *[[Herodotus]] mentions that it used to furnish the ancient Egyptian queens with sandals and other female goods.<ref name=PersGynaecopolis/> *It was assigned by Persian kings of Egypt to their queens, to provide them with sandals or girdles.<ref name=PersAnthylla/>
