[[File:Schenkelgau.png|thumb|Standard of the Letopolite [[nome (Egypt)|nome]]]]
[[File:Ushabti Ankh-hapi Bologna.JPG|thumb|Five faience ushabti of Ankh-hapi, a priest in Letopolis during the Ptolemaic dynasty. [[The Archaeological Civic Museum (MCA) of Bologna|Bologna, Museo Civico Archeologico]]]]
'''Letopolis''' ([[Greek language|Greek]]: Λητοῦς Πόλις) was an [[ancient Egypt]]ian city, the capital of the second [[nome (Egypt)|nome]] of [[Lower Egypt]]. Its [[Egyptian language|Egyptian]] name was '''Khem''' (Ḫm),<ref>Miriam Lichtheim, [https://books.google.com/books?id=Q2gRtLLmZTAC&pg=PA84&dq=%22khem%3Dletopolis%22&hl=en&sa=X&ei=7CkXVcGAHIaeNsXYgIAP&ved=0CEIQ6AEwBg#v=onepage&q=%22khem%3Dletopolis%22&f=false ''Ancient Egyptian Literature Vol. III: The Late Period''], Berkeley 1980, p.84</ref> and the modern site of its remains is known as '''Ausim'''.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.trismegistos.org/geo/detail.php?tm=1245|title=Trismegistos|website=www.trismegistos.org|access-date=2018-02-26}}</ref> The city was a center of worship of the deity [[Khenty-irty]] or Khenty-khem, a form of the god [[Horus]]. The site and its deity are mentioned in texts from as far back as the [[Old Kingdom of Egypt|Old Kingdom]] (c. 2686–2181 BC), and a temple to the god probably stood there very early in Egyptian history. The only known monuments at the site, however, date to the reigns of pharaohs from the [[Late Period of ancient Egypt|Late Period]] (664–332 BC): [[Necho II]], [[Psamtik II]], [[Hakor]], and [[Nectanebo I]].<ref>Wilkinson, Richard H. (2000). ''The Complete Temples of Ancient Egypt''. Thames & Hudson. p. 111</ref>

