[[File:Statue of Pharaoh Osorkon I-AO 9502-P5280216-gradient.jpg|thumb|Pharaoh Sekhemkheperre Osorkon I was the founder of Pi-Sekhemkheperre]]
'''Pi-Sekhemkheperre''' or '''Per-Sekhemkheperre''', was an [[ancient Egypt]]ian stronghold. Its name means ''"The estate of Sekhemkheperre"'', a reference to [[Osorkon I|Sekhemkheperre Osorkon I]], the pharaoh of the early [[22nd Dynasty]] who founded the fortress during his reign (about 922 to 887 BCE).{{sfn|Kitchen|1996|p=§ 263}} It has been suggested that its erection may be a symptom of the state of general insecurity in the country during the period.{{sfn|Aston|2005|p=66}}<br/>
Pi-Sekhemkheperre is at yet [[lost city|undiscovered]]{{sfn|Aston|2005|p=66}} but it is believed that it lies somewhere at the entrance of the [[Faiyum]], just north to [[Herakleopolis Magna]] in [[Middle Egypt]].{{sfn|Kitchen|1996|p=§ 263}}

The first known "Chief of Pi-Sekhemkheperre" was [[Nimlot C]] – a son of the 22nd Dynasty pharaoh [[Osorkon II]] – who also ruled the neighbouring city of Herakleopolis.{{sfn|Kitchen|1996|p=§ 263}} Shortly after Nimlot's rule, it appears that the fortress shifted allegiance to the rival [[23rd Dynasty]]: it is known that an official named Ewelhon was "Chief of Pi-Sekhemkheperre" in [[regnal year]] 6 of pharaoh [[Pedubast I]];{{sfn|Kitchen|1996|p=§ 300}} still later, the same office was held by the pharaoh-to-be [[Takelot III]].{{sfn|Kitchen|1996|p=§ 313}}<br/>
During the [[Nubia]]n invasion of the [[Nile valley]] led by pharaoh [[Piye]] of the [[25th Dynasty]], Pi-Sekhemkheperre was loyal to the "Chief of the [[Meshwesh|Ma]]" [[Tefnakht]] and his coalition. As stated on his ''Victory stela'', Piye found the stronghold garrisoned but was able to obtain its surrender without bloodshed, also capturing Tefnakht's son in the process.{{sfn|Breasted|1906|p=§§ 816ff}}

